# Cross-platform line-ending policy.
#
# This file is the source of truth for line endings in this repo and
# overrides every contributor's local `core.autocrlf` setting, so behavior
# is identical on Windows, macOS, and Linux regardless of how each
# machine's git is configured.
#
# Defaults:
#   * text=auto eol=lf
#     Auto-detect text vs binary; every text file is LF in both the git
#     index AND the working tree on every OS. Prevents Windows from
#     silently rewriting Unix-only files (.sh, Dockerfiles, makefiles,
#     /etc/ drop-ins) to CRLF — CRLF on those files breaks `/bin/bash`,
#     container builds, and most Unix parsers.
#
# Overrides:
#   *.ps1 / *.psm1 / *.psd1 / *.bat / *.cmd
#     CRLF in the working tree on every OS (LF in the index, as always —
#     git's index storage is always LF for text). Windows-native tooling
#     (cmd.exe, batch wrappers, Windows PowerShell 5.1 hosts, signing
#     tooling) round-trips correctly only with CRLF for these formats.
#
# Re-normalize the working tree after editing this file:
#
#   git add --renormalize .
#   git status            # review (line-ending-only, content unchanged)
#   git commit -m "chore: renormalize line endings"

* text=auto eol=lf

*.ps1   text eol=crlf
*.psm1  text eol=crlf
*.psd1  text eol=crlf
*.bat   text eol=crlf
*.cmd   text eol=crlf
